% Automatisch generiert — Thema: Cloning
% arg/1 Fakten
arg(pro9).  % [pro] The process of transplanting human organs can become simpler.
arg(pro9b).  % [pro] The process of transplanting human organs can have an immensely improved success rate.
arg(pro124).  % [pro] Parents that have lost a child can have that child returned to them with a clone.
arg(pro4).  % [pro] Mankind is already "playing" God when we cure diseases, fly airplanes, create nuclear energy, or use any advanced technology.
arg(pro53b).  % [pro] Access to a tremendous amount of information about a clone's parent could greatly help in understanding the clone's psyche and physical attributes.
arg(pro119).  % [pro] Using embryos in stem cell research could possibly save human lives.
arg(pro126).  % [pro] Cloning humans has the possibility of becoming safer than naturally developing embryos by replacing random risks and genetic defects.
arg(con72).  % [con] Cloned children would unavoidably be raised in the shadow of their nuclear donor.
arg(con72b).  % [con] Being raised in the shadow of their nuclear donor would strongly tend to constrain individual psychological and social development.
arg(con42).  % [con] Adopting an orphan is much easier than trying to clone a human being.
arg(con42b).  % [con] Adopting an orphan is much cheaper than trying to clone a human being.
arg(con42c).  % [con] Adopting an orphan is a virtuous solution compared to cloning a human being.
arg(con42d).  % [con] Adopting an orphan is a safer solution than trying to clone a human being.
arg(con42e).  % [con] Adopting an orphan helps a child in need, whereas cloning a human being does not.
arg(con9).  % [con] Ian Wilmut, the creator of Dolly, has denounced human reproductive cloning as too dangerous to attempt.
arg(con134).  % [con] If genes are modified to create beings who are smarter than others, the average person will not have a place in society.
arg(con126).  % [con] Large scale research cloning could generate a market for women's eggs that could easily lead to exploitation.
arg(con84b).  % [con] Cloning is considered unsafe because of the high failure rate due to genetic defects.
arg(con20).  % [con] This race could easily fall into slavery.

% att/2 Fakten  (Dung 1995 — binär; Typ/conf aus LLM-Kandidaten als Kommentar)
att(con9, pro9).  % [undermining] conf=80 — Con9 challenges the safety premise underlying pro9's claim that cloning could simplify organ transplants.
att(con126, pro9).  % [undermining] conf=70 — Con126 attacks the ethical premise of pro9 by highlighting potential exploitation in large‑scale cloning.
att(con84b, pro9).  % [undermining] conf=85 — Con84b directly undermines the assumption that cloning can safely simplify organ transplants by citing high failure rates.
att(con42, pro9).  % [undermining] conf=80 — Con42 challenges the feasibility premise of cloning by claiming adoption is easier than cloning.
att(con42b, pro9).  % [undermining] conf=80 — Con42b attacks the cost‑effectiveness premise of cloning by stating adoption is much cheaper.
att(con42c, pro9).  % [undermining] conf=75 — Con42c undermines the moral premise behind pro9 by asserting that adoption is a more virtuous alternative to cloning.
att(con84b, pro9b).  % [undermining] conf=80 — The con argument claims cloning is unsafe due to genetic defects, which attacks the premise that cloning will improve organ‑transplant success.
att(con72, pro124).  % [undermining] conf=85 — The con claim that cloned children will live in the donor’s shadow undermines the premise that cloning a lost child would be a satisfactory replacement for grieving parents.
att(con72b, pro124).  % [undermining] conf=85 — The argument that being raised in the donor’s shadow constrains development attacks the same premise of the pro argument, questioning the benefit of cloning a lost child.
att(con42, pro124).  % [undermining] conf=70 — B claims adoption is easier, challenging the premise that cloning is a practical option.
att(con42b, pro124).  % [undermining] conf=75 — B argues adoption is cheaper, attacking the cost‑feasibility premise of cloning.
att(con42c, pro124).  % [undermining] conf=70 — B asserts adoption is virtuous, undermining any moral premise supporting cloning.
att(con42d, pro124).  % [undermining] conf=80 — B says adoption is safer, attacking the safety premise of cloning.
att(con42e, pro124).  % [undermining] conf=75 — B highlights that adoption helps a child while cloning does not, challenging the social‑benefit premise of cloning.
att(con9, pro124).  % [rebuttal] conf=85 — B cites an expert who denounces human cloning as dangerous, directly contradicting the feasibility claim of A.
att(con126, pro124).  % [undermining] conf=80 — B warns of a market for women’s eggs and exploitation, attacking the ethical premise of cloning.
att(con84b, pro124).  % [rebuttal] conf=85 — B points to high failure rates and genetic defects, directly contradicting the claim that cloning can safely return a child.
